aVMany years ago I heard a mathematician from Vienna, whose name was Marchetti,
p284
aVexplain how the innovation in the military industry \u2014
p285
aVtherefore, secret innovation \u2014 and the innovation in the
p286
aVcivilian society are two sinusoids that are kind of opposed.
p287
aVAnd that makes sense.
p288
aVIn moments of war there's great technological innovation,
p289
aVand in the world you have to do without \u2014
p290
aVwell, during the Second World War, you had to do without steel,
p291
aVyou had to do without aluminum.
p292
aVAnd then as peace comes, all of these technologies get all of a sudden
p293
aVavailable for the civilian market.
p294
aVMany of you might know that the Potato Chip Chair
p295
aVby Charles and Ray Eames comes exactly from that kind of instance:
p296
aVfiberglass was available for civilian use all of a sudden.
